</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Helminthic diseases have a worldwide distribution. They affect billions of people in endemic areas and can result in serious clinical complications. Some parasites have a human gastrointestinal life cycle with resultant abdominal manifestations. However, the symptoms of helminthic diseases are usually nonspecific. Radiologic imaging, along with the identification of risk factors, may help narrow the differential diagnosis. To avoid diagnostic delays, radiologists should be familiar with the geographic distribution, transmission cycle, and characteristic and atypical manifestations of common helminthic diseases at abdominal imaging with radiography, computed tomography, magnetic resonance imaging, and ultrasonography. Awareness of the clinical, epidemiologic, and pathogenic characteristics of these diseases also may be helpful for narrowing the diagnosis when imaging features are nonspecific.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.301095092">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.301095092">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c01x.jpeg" height="747" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f1-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Map shows the world distribution of the three most common <i>Schistosoma</i> species (regions in red): <i>S japonicum,</i> in China and the Philippines; <i>S haematobium</i>, in Africa and the Middle East; and <i>S mansoni</i>, in South America, Africa, and the Middle East. <i>S mansoni</i> is the only species that has been observed to cause schistosomiasis in South America.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f1-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g10x.jpeg" height="1412" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f10-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span> Intestinal strongyloidiasis. Image from a barium study of the upper digestive tract shows diffuse effacement of the mucosal folds in the duodenum and proximal jejunum (arrow). (Courtesy of Luiz Nunes de Oliveira, MD, Instituto da Criança do HCFMUSP, São Paulo, Brazil.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f10-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g11x.jpeg" height="1682" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f11-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span> Obstructive jaundice as a complication of strongyloidiasis. Oblique coronal reformatted image from abdominal CT shows biliary dilatation, with the papilla bulging into the duodenal lumen (arrows). At biopsy, an inflammatory infiltration of eosinophils was seen; no neoplastic cells were observed. A stool examination was positive for <i>S stercoralis</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f11-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c12x.jpeg" height="772" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f12-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Map shows the world distribution of <i>A lumbricoides</i> and <i>Trichuris trichiura</i> in tropical and subtropical regions, where the air temperature and humidity are conducive to the embryony of parasite eggs.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f12-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c13x.jpeg" height="1280" width="1153" aria-labelledby="f13-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> Diagram shows the life cycle of <i>A lumbricoides</i>. Eggs eliminated in the feces <i>(<a href="#b1-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b1-0300253">1</a>)</i> become embryonate and infective within 18 days. After the eggs are swallowed <i>(<a href="#b2-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b2-0300253">2</a>)</i>, larvae hatch, invade the intestinal mucosa <i>(<a href="#b3-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b3-0300253">3</a>)</i>, and migrate through the portal <i>(<a href="#b4-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b4-0300253">4</a>)</i> and systemic circulation to the lungs <i>(<a href="#b5-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b5-0300253">5</a>)</i>, where they ascend the bronchial tree, enter the esophagus, and are again swallowed. In the small intestine <i>(<a href="#b6-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b6-0300253">6</a>)</i>, the larvae mature into adult worms.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f13-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f14-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g14x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1549" aria-labelledby="f14-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span> Image from a barium study in a child with abdominal pain shows elongated radiolucent filling defects (arrow). The final diagnosis was ascariasis. (Courtesy of Luiz Nunes de Oliveira, MD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f14-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f15-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g15x.jpeg" height="1258" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f15-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> US image obtained in a patient with non-specific abdominal pain shows the digestive tract of a worm as two parallel echogenic lines (arrows). <i>Ascaris</i> was identified at stool analysis. (Courtesy of Miguel José Francisco Neto, MD, Departamento de Radiologia da Faculdade de Medicina da Universidade de São Paulo, São Paulo, Brazil.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f15-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g16x.jpeg" height="1548" width="1402" aria-labelledby="f16-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span> Radiograph obtained in a child with acute abdominal symptoms shows a dilated bowel loop containing an aggregation of thick tubular structures (arrow), a feature that represents an <i>Ascaris</i> worm bolus. (Courtesy of Luiz Nunes de Oliveira, MD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f16-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f17a-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g17a.jpeg" height="1208" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f17a-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium study performed in a patient with abdominal pain after an episode of acute pancreatitis shows an elongated filling defect within the main pancreatic duct (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Image from endoscopy shows a roundworm of the <i>Ascaris</i> species emerging from the ampulla of Vater (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f17a-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f17b-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c17b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1248" aria-labelledby="f17b-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium study performed in a patient with abdominal pain after an episode of acute pancreatitis shows an elongated filling defect within the main pancreatic duct (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Image from endoscopy shows a roundworm of the <i>Ascaris</i> species emerging from the ampulla of Vater (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f17b-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f18-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c18x.jpeg" height="1280" width="1205" aria-labelledby="f18-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span> Diagram shows the life cycle of <i>T trichiura</i>. Eggs eliminated in feces <i>(<a href="#b1-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b1-0300253">1</a>)</i> become embryonate in the soil. After the eggs are swallowed <i>(<a href="#b2-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b2-0300253">2</a>)</i>, larvae hatch in the small intestine and migrate to the cecum and ascending colon <i>(<a href="#b3-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b3-0300253">3</a>)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f18-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f19a-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g19a.jpeg" height="1319" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f19a-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium enema examination in a 4-year-old patient with rectal bleeding and anemia shows mucosal thickening and multiple tiny filling defects with a curvilinear shape (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Image from colonoscopy shows multiple <i>T trichiura</i> worms attached to the cecum. (Case courtesy of Luiz Nunes de Oliveira, MD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f19a-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f19b-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c19b.jpeg" height="1140" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f19b-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium enema examination in a 4-year-old patient with rectal bleeding and anemia shows mucosal thickening and multiple tiny filling defects with a curvilinear shape (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Image from colonoscopy shows multiple <i>T trichiura</i> worms attached to the cecum. (Case courtesy of Luiz Nunes de Oliveira, MD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f19b-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c02x.jpeg" height="1280" width="1189" aria-labelledby="f2-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Diagram shows the life cycle of <i>S mansoni,</i> which begins with the excretion of eggs in human feces <i>(<a href="#b1-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b1-0300253">1</a>)</i>. If the eggs reach water, miracidia hatch <i>(<a href="#b2-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b2-0300253">2</a>)</i> and may infect snails <i>(<a href="#b3-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b3-0300253">3</a>)</i>. Inside a snail, miracidia mature into cercariae <i>(<a href="#b4-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b4-0300253">4</a>)</i>. After their secretion by the snail, the cercariae swim until they come into contact with and penetrate the skin of a human host <i>(<a href="#b5-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b5-0300253">5</a>)</i>. They migrate via blood and lymph vessels to the lungs <i>(<a href="#b6-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b6-0300253">6</a>)</i> and liver <i>(<a href="#b7-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b7-0300253">7</a>)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f2-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f20-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c20x.jpeg" height="774" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f20-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span> Map shows the world distribution of <i>T solium</i>. Red represents highly endemic regions, and dark green, suspected endemic regions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f20-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f21-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c21x.jpeg" height="1280" width="1104" aria-labelledby="f21-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span> Diagram shows the life cycle of <i>T solium</i>. Eggs eliminated in feces <i>(<a href="#b1-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b1-0300253">1</a>)</i> are ingested by an intermediate host (usually pigs) and hatch into larvae that invade the intestinal mucosa <i>(<a href="#b2-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b2-0300253">2</a>)</i> and migrate to muscle, where they develop into cysticerci <i>(<a href="#b3-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b3-0300253">3</a>)</i>. When humans, the definitive hosts, ingest cysticerci in pork that is insufficiently cooked <i>(<a href="#b4-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b4-0300253">4</a>)</i>, adult worms develop in the small intestine <i>(<a href="#b5-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b5-0300253">5</a>)</i>; this type of infection is called taeniasis. When humans ingest the eggs <i>(<a href="#b6-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b6-0300253">6</a>)</i>, cysticerci develop in the muscle, the brain, or the eyes; this type of infection is called cysticercosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f21-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f22-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g22x.jpeg" height="1266" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f22-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span> Muscular cysticercosis. Axial CT image shows rice-grain–like calcifications in the muscles, findings that represent granulomas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f22-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f23-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c23x.jpeg" height="772" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f23-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span> Map shows the world distribution of <i>Echinococcus</i> species: <i>E granulosus</i> is endemic in the red areas, and <i>E vogeli</i> is endemic in the dark green areas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f23-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f24-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c24x.jpeg" height="1186" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f24-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span> Diagram shows the life cycle of <i>E granulosus</i>. Intermediate and definitive hosts must coexist for the life cycle to be completed: Adult worms living in the intestines of dogs release eggs <i>(<a href="#b1-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b1-0300253">1</a>)</i>, which are ingested by sheep. When a human swallows the eggs <i>(<a href="#b2-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b2-0300253">2</a>)</i>, oncospheres hatch in the intestine and, from there, burrow into other organs (blue arrows), such as the liver, spleen, and lungs, where they form hydatid cysts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f24-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f25-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g25x.jpeg" height="1458" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f25-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows multiple simple hydatid cysts, as well as cysts within a cyst surrounded by a fibrous low-signal-intensity capsule (arrows), within the liver of a patient with echinococcosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f25-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f26-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g26x.jpeg" height="1280" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f26-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span> Axial CT image shows a typical unilocular hydatid cyst with peripheral calcification (arrow) in the spleen of a patient with echinococcosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f26-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f27a-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g27a.jpeg" height="1211" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f27a-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27a</span> <i>E granulosus</i> infection in a Bolivian female shepherd with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT scan shows a large septate cyst containing smaller cysts (arrows) in the right hepatic lobe. The differential diagnosis included hydatid cyst and biliary cystadenoma. A right hepatectomy was performed. <b>(b)</b> Photograph shows the excised cyst, which contained yellowish fluid and multiple smaller cysts within a thick capsule. The patient recovered well after surgical treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f27a-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f27b-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c27b.jpeg" height="1142" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f27b-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27b</span> <i>E granulosus</i> infection in a Bolivian female shepherd with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT scan shows a large septate cyst containing smaller cysts (arrows) in the right hepatic lobe. The differential diagnosis included hydatid cyst and biliary cystadenoma. A right hepatectomy was performed. <b>(b)</b> Photograph shows the excised cyst, which contained yellowish fluid and multiple smaller cysts within a thick capsule. The patient recovered well after surgical treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f27b-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f28-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g28x.jpeg" height="1644" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f28-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28</span> Axial T2-weighted MR image obtained in a patient with jaundice shows multiple hepatic cysts suggestive of echinococcosis. Associated biliary compression and biliary dilatation also are shown.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f28-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f29-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g29x.jpeg" height="1504" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f29-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29</span> Echinococcosis due to <i>E vogeli</i> in a patient from an area of northern Brazil that is inhabited by pacas. Coronal T2-weighted fat-suppressed MR image shows multiple cysts disseminated throughout the liver parenchyma and peritoneum (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f29-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g03x.jpeg" height="1388" width="1728" aria-labelledby="f3-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span> Hepatosplenic schistosomiasis with portal hypertension. Axial CT scan shows hepatic architectural distortion with atrophy of the right hepatic lobe, widening of hepatic fissures (arrows), and splenomegaly.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f3-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f30-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c30x.jpeg" height="1203" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f30-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30</span> Diagram shows the life cycle of <i>T canis</i>. Humans are infected after ingesting eggs <i>(<a href="#b1-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b1-0300253">1</a>)</i> from the soil or encapsulated larvae in meat that is insufficiently cooked <i>(<a href="#b2-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b2-0300253">2</a>)</i>. The larvae are liberated in the intestine <i>(<a href="#b3-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b3-0300253">3</a>)</i>, invade the intestinal wall, and spread to the liver and other tissues (blue arrows), where they induce eosinophilic abscesses or granuloma formation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f30-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f31-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g31x.jpeg" height="1372" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f31-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31</span> Axial CT scan obtained in a patient with a fever of unknown cause shows multiple ill-defined nonspecific hepatic lesions with peripheral enhancement (arrows). The subsequent diagnosis was toxocariasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f31-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f32-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c32x.jpeg" height="774" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f32-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32</span> Map shows the distribution of <i>A costaricensis</i> in Central America, where it is endemic, and in South America, where it is sporadic.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f32-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f33-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c33x.jpeg" height="1250" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f33-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 33</span> Diagram shows the life cycle of <i>A costaricensis</i>. In the first stage of transmission (green arrows), rats eliminate feces that contain eggs <i>(<a href="#b1-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b1-0300253">1</a>)</i>, which are ingested by or penetrate snails or slugs <i>(<a href="#b2-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b2-0300253">2</a>)</i>. The snails and slugs secrete mucus that contains larvae. Humans are infected when they ingest food contaminated with the larvae (blue arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f33-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f34a-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g34a.jpeg" height="1282" width="1710" aria-labelledby="f34a-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 34a</span> Atypical angiostrongylosis of the small bowel and liver in a 55-year-old man with abdominal pain, peritonitis, and peripheral blood eosinophilia. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images depict multiple ill-defined non-specific hypoattenuating lesions in the liver parenchyma (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) with small-bowel wall thickening (arrows in <b>b</b>). An enterectomy was performed. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; hematoxylin-eosin stain) of a histologic slice shows the parasite inside a mesenteric arteriole (arrow) with surrounding eosinophilic inflammatory infiltrate. (Fig 34c courtesy of Thales de Brito, MD, PhD, and Fernando Aguiar, MD, Departamento de Patologia da Faculdade de Medicina da Universidade de São Paulo, São Paulo, Brazil.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f34a-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f34b-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g34b.jpeg" height="1401" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f34b-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 34b</span> Atypical angiostrongylosis of the small bowel and liver in a 55-year-old man with abdominal pain, peritonitis, and peripheral blood eosinophilia. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images depict multiple ill-defined non-specific hypoattenuating lesions in the liver parenchyma (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) with small-bowel wall thickening (arrows in <b>b</b>). An enterectomy was performed. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; hematoxylin-eosin stain) of a histologic slice shows the parasite inside a mesenteric arteriole (arrow) with surrounding eosinophilic inflammatory infiltrate. (Fig 34c courtesy of Thales de Brito, MD, PhD, and Fernando Aguiar, MD, Departamento de Patologia da Faculdade de Medicina da Universidade de São Paulo, São Paulo, Brazil.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f34b-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f34c-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c34c.jpeg" height="958" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f34c-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 34c</span> Atypical angiostrongylosis of the small bowel and liver in a 55-year-old man with abdominal pain, peritonitis, and peripheral blood eosinophilia. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images depict multiple ill-defined non-specific hypoattenuating lesions in the liver parenchyma (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) with small-bowel wall thickening (arrows in <b>b</b>). An enterectomy was performed. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; hematoxylin-eosin stain) of a histologic slice shows the parasite inside a mesenteric arteriole (arrow) with surrounding eosinophilic inflammatory infiltrate. (Fig 34c courtesy of Thales de Brito, MD, PhD, and Fernando Aguiar, MD, Departamento de Patologia da Faculdade de Medicina da Universidade de São Paulo, São Paulo, Brazil.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f34c-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g04x.jpeg" height="1359" width="1692" aria-labelledby="f4-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span> Advanced hepatosplenic schistosomiasis. Sagittal paramedian US image shows thickening of the gallbladder wall (arrow) and periportal hyperechogenicity (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f4-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5a-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g05a.jpeg" height="1450" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5a-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Hepatosplenic schistosomiasis with marked periportal fibrosis. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced T2-weighted MR image shows high-signal-intensity bands along the portal tracts (<b>*</b>) and splenomegaly with siderotic nodules (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image obtained during the venous phase shows enhanced periportal bands (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f5a-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5b-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g05b.jpeg" height="1478" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5b-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Hepatosplenic schistosomiasis with marked periportal fibrosis. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced T2-weighted MR image shows high-signal-intensity bands along the portal tracts (<b>*</b>) and splenomegaly with siderotic nodules (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image obtained during the venous phase shows enhanced periportal bands (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f5b-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g06x.jpeg" height="1272" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span> Axial CT image shows exuberant paraesophageal collateral circulation due to thrombosis and cavernous transformation of the portal vein and thrombosis of the splenic vein in a patient with schistosomiasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f6-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7a-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g07a.jpeg" height="1352" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7a-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Hepatosplenic schistosomiasis after splenectomy. <b>(a)</b> MR cholangiopancreatographic image shows intrahepatic biliary dilatation and gallstones. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image obtained during the venous phase shows compression of the main hepatic duct with associated cholangiopathy (arrow) due to thrombosis and cavernous transformation of the portal vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f7a-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7b-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092g07b.jpeg" height="1374" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7b-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Hepatosplenic schistosomiasis after splenectomy. <b>(a)</b> MR cholangiopancreatographic image shows intrahepatic biliary dilatation and gallstones. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image obtained during the venous phase shows compression of the main hepatic duct with associated cholangiopathy (arrow) due to thrombosis and cavernous transformation of the portal vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f7b-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c08x.jpeg" height="768" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f8-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Map shows the world distribution of <i>S stercoralis</i>, which is endemic in many tropical and subtropical regions of Asia, Africa, and South America and prevalent in the southeastern United States.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f8-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9-0300253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095092/asset/images/g095092c09x.jpeg" height="1280" width="1156" aria-labelledby="f9-0300253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Diagram shows the life cycle of <i>S stercoralis,</i> which begins when eggs eliminated in human feces <i>(<a href="#b1-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b1-0300253">1</a>)</i> reach the soil <i>(<a href="#b2-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b2-0300253">2</a>)</i>, where the larvae hatch. At contact with a human host, the infective larvae penetrate the skin <i>(<a href="#b3-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b3-0300253">3</a>)</i>, migrate to the lungs <i>(<a href="#b4-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b4-0300253">4</a>)</i>, and ascend the bronchial tree to the esophagus, at which point they are swallowed. In the small intestine, the larvae mature into worms <i>(<a href="#b5-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b5-0300253">5</a>)</i>. A unique pattern of continuous auto-infection may become established <i>(<a href="#b6-0300253" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b6-0300253">6</a>)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095092&amp;id=f9-0300253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="b1-0300253" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Savioli L, Stansfield S, Bundg DAP, et al.Schistosomiasis and soil-transmitted helminth infections: forging control efforts. <em>Trans R Soc Trop Med Hyg</em> 2002;96(6):577–579.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0035-9203(02)90316-0">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12625126/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Schistosomiasis+and+soil-transmitted+helminth+infections%3A+forging+control+efforts&amp;author=L+Savioli&amp;author=S+Stansfield&amp;author=DAP+Bundg&amp;publication_year=2002&amp;journal=Trans+R+Soc+Trop+Med+Hyg&amp;pages=577-579&amp;doi=10.1016%2FS0035-9203%2802%2990316-0&amp;pmid=12625126">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="b2-0300253" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Craig P, Ito AIntestinal cestodes. <em>Curr Opin Infect Dis</em> 2007;20:524–532.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/QCO.0b013e3282ef579e">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17762788/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Intestinal+cestodes&amp;author=P+Craig&amp;author=A+Ito&amp;publication_year=2007&amp;journal=Curr+Opin+Infect+Dis&amp;pages=524-532&amp;doi=10.1097%2FQCO.0b013e3282ef579e&amp;pmid=17762788">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="b3-0300253" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">World Health Organization. Control of neurocysticercosis: report by the Secretariat, provisional agenda item 14.2, 56th World Health Assembly, Geneva, Switzerland [document online]. <a href="http://apps.who.int/gb/archive/pdf_files/WHA56/ea5610.pdf">http://apps.who.int/gb/archive/pdf_files/WHA56/ea5610.pdf</a>. Published March 6, 2003. <span class="named-content" data-type="access-date">Accessed October 19, 2009</span>.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Control+of+neurocysticercosis%3A+report+by+the+Secretariat%2C+provisional+agenda+item+14.2">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">4.</div><div id="b4-0300253" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Manzella A, Ohtomo K, Monzawa S, Lim JHSchistosomiasis of the liver. <em>Abdom Imaging</em> 2008;33: 144–150.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00261-007-9329-7">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17912583/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Schistosomiasis+of+the+liver&amp;author=A+Manzella&amp;